03228nam a22004215i 9780300241389DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002413897 a10.12987/97803002413892doi  a(DE-B1597)536125  a(OCoLC)1125187044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0140002bisacsh1 aBeyerchen, Alan D., eauthor.10aScientists under Hitler :bPolitics and the Physics Community in the Third Reich /cAlan D. Beyerchen. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Background -- t2. Gottingen-1933 -- t3. The Toll of the Dismissal Policy -- t4. The Government and the Physics Professoriate -- t5. The Aryan Physicists: Philipp Lenard -- t6. The Aryan Physicists: Johannes Stark -- t7. Aryan Physics -- t8. The Aryan Physics Political Campaign -- t9. The War Years -- t10. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe treatment of German physicists under the Nazi regime had far-reaching consequences both for the outcome of the Second World War and for the course of science for decades thereafter. Although this fact has been known from a few famous episodes, it has not been dealt with thoroughly by scholars because it involves two very different disciplines. Political historians have cautiously left it to historians of science, who in turn have shied away from it out of ignorance of the political intricacies. Alan D. Beyerchen here examines this history in detail, basing his research on archival materials in Germany and the United States and on tape-recorded interviews with leading physicists. At least twenty-five percent of Germany's academic physicists who were working in 1933 lost their positions during the Nazi period. The victims -- Jews and other ";politically unreliable"; persons -- included some of Germany's finest scientists. Those who remained faced opposition not only from Nazi officials but also from certain members of their own community, notably the Nobel laureates Philipp Lenard and Johannes Stark. Beyerchen describes the mechanisms of prejudice, the reaction to the dismissals, and the impact of the ";Aryan physics"; movement which ultimately failed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300241389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780300241389.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles